05966nam a22007335i 9781501716133DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019001071  a97815017161337 a10.1515/97815017161332doi  a(DE-B1597)527444  a(OCoLC)1082297589  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aE269.I5 4aE269.I5bH47 2020 7aHIS0271102bisacsh04a973.32231 aHerrmann, Rachel B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Useless Mouth :bWaging War and Fighting Hunger in the American Revolution /cRachel B. Herrmann. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (300 p.) :b5 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Why the Fight against Hunger Mattered -- tPart One: Power Rising -- t1. Hunger, Accommodation, and Violence in Colonial America -- t2. Iroquois Food Diplomacy in the Revolutionary North -- t3. Cherokee and Creek Victual Warfare in the Revolutionary South -- tPart Two: Power in Flux -- t4. Black Victual Warriors and Hunger Creation -- t5. Fighting Hunger, Fearing Violence after the Revolutionary War -- t6. Learning from Food Laws in Nova Scotia -- tPart Three: Power Waning -- t7. Victual Imperialism and U.S. Indian Policy -- t8. Black Loyalist Hunger Prevention in Sierra Leone -- tConclusion: Why Native and Black Revolutionaries Lost the Fight -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliographic Note -- tNotes -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIn the era of the American Revolution, the rituals of diplomacy between the British, Patriots, and Native Americans featured gifts of food, ceremonial feasts, and a shared experience of hunger. When diplomacy failed, Native Americans could destroy food stores and cut off supply chains in order to assert authority. Black colonists also stole and destroyed food to ward off hunger and carve out tenuous spaces of freedom. Hunger was a means of power and a weapon of war.In No Useless Mouth Rachel B. Herrmann argues that Native Americans and formerly enslaved black colonists ultimately lost the battle against hunger and the larger struggle for power because white British and United States officials curtailed the abilities of men and women to fight hunger on their own terms. By describing three interrelated behaviors-food diplomacy, victual imperialism, and victual warfare-the book shows that, during this tumultuous period, hunger prevention efforts offered strategies to claim power, maintain communities, and keep rival societies at bay.Herrmann shows how Native Americans, free blacks, and enslaved peoples were "useful mouths"-not mere supplicants for food, without rights or power-who used hunger for cooperation and violence, and took steps to circumvent starvation. Her wide-ranging research on black Loyalists, Iroquois, Cherokee, Creek, and Western Confederacy Indians demonstrates that hunger creation and prevention were tools of diplomacy and warfare available to all people involved in the American Revolution. Placing hunger at the center of these struggles foregrounds the contingency and plurality of power in the British Atlantic during the Revolutionary Era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxFoodxHistoryy18th century. 0aFood securityzNova ScotiaxHistoryy18th century. 0aFood securityzSierra LeonexHistoryy18th century. 0aFood securityzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxFoodxHistoryy18th century. 4aDiscrimina